# 🚀 Day 1 – Real-Time Delivery Tracking System

## 📌 Overview

Today I started building a real-time delivery tracking system similar to apps like Uber/Zomato. The goal was to understand how live location updates work without refreshing the app, using WebSockets.

---

## 🛠️ What I Built

* Set up a Node.js backend server
* Implemented real-time communication using Socket.IO
* Created an **agent simulator** that sends location updates every 2 seconds
* Built a simple frontend (`index.html`) to display live location
* Enabled real-time broadcasting from server → multiple clients

---

## ⚙️ How It Works

* The **agent** sends location updates to the server
* The **server** receives and broadcasts them
* The **frontend** listens and updates UI instantly

This creates a **live tracking experience without refresh**

---

## 🧱 Challenges I Faced

### 1. Node.js & npm not recognized

* Faced multiple PATH and installation issues
* Fixed by reinstalling Node.js properly and configuring environment variables

---

### 2. Permission Errors (EPERM)

* Could not create `package.json`
* Root cause: folder permission / file lock issue
* Solution: created a fresh project folder (clean environment approach)

---

### 3. Wrong Project Setup

* Accidentally had Node binaries inside project folder
* Learned separation between **system tools vs project files**

---

### 4. Frontend Not Updating (Major Issue)

* Browser showed “Waiting…” even though backend was working
* Root causes:

  * Opening file via `file://`
  * Socket.IO CDN mismatch
  * Incorrect connection handling

✅ Fix:

* Served frontend via Express (`app.use(express.static(__dirname))`)
* Used `/socket.io/socket.io.js` instead of CDN
* Connected using `io()` instead of hardcoded URL

---

## 🧠 Key Learnings

* Real-time systems use **event-driven architecture**
* WebSockets enable instant updates without refresh
* Environment setup is as important as coding
* Debugging is a core skill in development
* Always serve frontend via server (not file system)

---

## 🎯 Outcome

Successfully built a working **real-time tracking system** where:

* Agent sends live location
* Server processes it
* Multiple clients receive updates instantly

